{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538958"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:35:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:35:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16422"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16422","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16422"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.6,0.07,0.03,0.12,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9113"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65158"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9113"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16422"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50595"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4128"},{"type":"tags","id":"5320"},{"type":"tags","id":"11059"},{"type":"tags","id":"12245"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21651"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65158","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65158"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of frequent hot flushes and night sweats that are affecting her sleep and quality of life. She underwent total laparoscopic hysterectomy and bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy two years ago for benign ovarian cysts. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never smoked and drinks minimal alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 24 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate hormone replacement therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oestrogen-only patch","Progesterone-only tablet","Tibolone","Combined oestrogen and progesterone patch","Combined oral oestrogen and progesterone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is experiencing significant vasomotor symptoms following surgical menopause due to bilateral oophorectomy. Given her previous hysterectomy, she has no uterus and therefore does not require endometrial protection with progesterone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen-only patch\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice as it will effectively treat her symptoms without unnecessary exposure to progesterone. Transdermal administration has advantages over oral administration, including bypass of first-pass metabolism and lower thrombotic risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oral oestrogen and progesterone\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for women with an intact uterus who require endometrial protection, but is unnecessary in this case and would expose the patient to unnecessary progesterone-related side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibolone\u003C/strong\u003E is a synthetic steroid with combined oestrogenic, progestogenic, and androgenic effects. While it can be effective for menopausal symptoms, oestrogen-only therapy would be more appropriate in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgesterone-only tablet\u003C/strong\u003E would not adequately address her symptoms as oestrogen is the primary hormone needed to treat vasomotor symptoms. Progesterone is only needed for endometrial protection in women with an intact uterus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oestrogen and progesterone patch\u003C/strong\u003E, like oral combined therapy, would unnecessarily expose the patient to progesterone when she has no uterus requiring protection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe choice of hormone replacement therapy should be individualised based on patient factors including the presence or absence of a uterus, risk factors, and patient preference. In women who have had a hysterectomy, oestrogen-only therapy is preferred as it has a more favourable risk profile than combined therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Women who have had a hysterectomy require oestrogen-only hormone replacement therapy as there is no need for progesterone protection of the endometrium.","Oestrogen-only hormone replacement therapy has a more favourable risk profile than combined therapy.","Vasomotor symptoms are the most common indication for starting hormone replacement therapy in post-menopausal women."],"references":["Australasian Menopause Society. Oestrogen-only menopausal hormone therapy (MHT) [Internet]. East Melbourne: Australasian Menopause Society; c2023 [cited 2024 Nov 25]. Available from: https://www.menopause.org.au/hp/information-sheets/oestrogen-only-mht"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50595"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16422"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50595"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T17:59:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T18:00:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9113"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65158"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"desc